  "local_port": 49672,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I remove the HTC One X System folder, which still appears on my Windows 7 list of devices?",
  "response": "The HTC One X System folder appearing in your Windows 7 list of devices is likely a leftover from a previous connection of your HTC One X device to your computer. To remove it, you can try the following steps:\n\n### Step 1: Disconnect and Reconnect the Device\n\n1. **Disconnect your HTC One X from your computer** if it is currently connected.\n2. **Restart your computer** to ensure any temporary connections are cleared.\n3. **Reconnect your HTC One X** to see if the issue persists.\n\n### Step 2: Update Device Drivers\n\nSometimes, outdated or corrupted drivers can cause issues with device recognition.\n\n1. Open **Device Manager** on your Windows 7 computer. You can do this by pressing `Win + X` and selecting Device Manager.\n2. Look for your HTC One X under **Portable Devices** or **Other Devices**.\n3. Right-click on the device and select **Update Driver Software**.\n4. Choose **Search automatically for updated driver software** and follow the prompts.\n\n### Step 3: Uninstall the Device\n\nIf updating the drivers doesn't help, you can try uninstalling the device.\n\n1. In **Device Manager**, find your HTC One X.\n2. Right-click on the device and select **Uninstall**.\n3. Confirm the uninstallation and restart your computer.\n4. Reconnect your HTC One X to see if the issue is resolved.\n\n### Step 4: Clear the Device Cache\n\n1. Open **Disk Management**. You can do this by pressing `Win + R`, typing `diskmgmt.msc`, and pressing Enter.\n2. Look for any drives labeled as HTC One X or similar.\n3. If you find any, right-click on them and select **Change Drive Letter and Paths**.\n4. If a drive letter is assigned, click **Remove** and confirm.\n5. Restart your computer and reconnect your HTC One X.\n\n### Step 5: Use the Windows Troubleshooter\n\nWindows 7 has a built-in troubleshooter that can help resolve device issues.\n\n1. Open **Control Panel**.\n2. Go to **Troubleshooting** and then **Configure a device**.\n3. Follow the prompts to see if the troubleshooter can resolve the issue.\n\n### Step 6: Manually Remove Registry Entries\n\n**Caution:** Editing the registry can be risky. Make sure to back up your registry before proceeding.\n\n1. Press `Win + R`, type `regedit`, and press Enter to open the Registry Editor.\n2. Navigate to `HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Enum\\USB`.\n3. Search for any entries related to your HTC One X.\n4. Right-click on the relevant entries and select **Delete**.\n5. Restart your computer and reconnect your HTC One X.\n\nIf none of these steps resolve the issue, you might need to consider a more thorough system cleanup or consult with a professional technician.",
